title: For Sale/Trade:  Nazi Marked FN Browning 1922, Matching Numbers, Two Original Magazines
postcontent: For sale or trade:  Nazi marked .32acp FN Browning 1922 pistol with all matching numbers, and two original magazines.  This pistol is rather rare in the fact that it has two different Waffenamt numbers, which would make it a transitional pistol.  The slide and barrel both have WaA 613 and WaA 103.  There were approximately 3000 pistols with WaA 613.  There are only a few known pistols to have both of these WaA numbers.  I don't know if it increases the value of it, but it's still a very neat variation.  The bore is in excellent condition, almost like new.  It functions flawlessly.  I bought this pistol directly from a local veteran's estate in 2013.  After getting the pistol, I noticed that it had a very distinct pitting pattern on the slide.  I asked the vet's son about it later and he said "My father always told us that he took it off a dead Luftwaffe soldier.  It was blood that he didn't whipe off until a couple days later".  It really does look like blood pitting, but be your own judge.  The price on this pistol is $550 or best offer.  I will meet in person or ship to an FFL or C&R.  I have additional pictures I can send.

title: For Sale:  Remington 1858 Army. Heavy Indian wars usage with Indian decorated
postcontent: <<<If a serious collector with genuine interest in this gun who has suitable collector credentials as well as suitable financial credentials, would like to see it prior to actually buying it, I will send it to them for their inspection with no upfront money. Suitable collector credentials does not mean that one 'has a bunch of guns'. It means that one is experienced in original American Indian artifacts, and that one owns ANTIQUE pistols in the multi thousand dollar range. Please message me if you are interested. This piece is EXACTLY what I say it is.>>>This is an exceptional 1858 Remington Army .44 percussion pistol. Used by the Union Army during the Civil War and has quite visible inspectors marks. While original Indian decorated stocks on rifles are occasionally seen, in more than fifty years of collecting antique percussion weapons this is the only original Indian decorated pistol I have ever actually seen in real life, and it unquestionably saw battle during both the Civil War and the Indian Wars. It is well used but indexes and locks up solidly. It WOULD fire but is not being sold for use and there are no warranties as to use of any kind. There are six brass inlays on each grip. Five on each side are star shaped grommets, while the sixth on each side are thumbwheels from a small oil lamp of the period with some of the markings on them present. A thumbwheel is what is used to raise and lower the wick. They are from an early Holmes, Booth, and Haydens kerosene lamp, and show some of the markings and patent date. As the Indians did not use kerosene lamps in their villages these thumbwheels were likely taken off of a lamp that was destroyed during an Indian raid on a settler's wagon or home. The grips are in good condition considering their heavy usage. One heel chip is missing, and the other was chipped and repaired in the 19th century with brass nails. We virtually never know where a gun might actually have been used, or who might have used it. But this exceptionally rare piece certainly originally saw Union usage and likely was taken from the hand of a dead soldier at some point and later from the hand of the Indian who had carried it through wars and battles. In Indian ownership this would have been a highly prized item. A brave might have owned a rifle but nothing like this, and it would have likely been owned and carried by a tribal Chief. While Indians used rifles for both combat and hunting, a pistol, like a war club, was used almost exclusively for close up point blank combat and execution of wounded enemies. This is an exceptional pistol and would grace any museum level collection. You'll not likely ever see another. Please email any questions. Trades for antique pre 1898 weapons are possible. Thank you.
